  1. According to the cross-validation approach with LOOCV, the optimal level of tree complexity is 4. Although adding a second-order polynomial would increase the MSE, compared with the MSE of the model only having the linear term, we could get lower MSE (also compared to the MSE with only the linear term) after adding the fourth-order polynomial. However, the MSE would greatly increase after adding the fifth-order polynomial. So the optimal level of tree complexity is 4.

Part 2: Modeling voter turnout

Preparation: split the data into a training set (70%) and a validation set (30%).

1. Five tree-based models of voter turnout

1.1 classification tree

Using a k-fold CV where k = 15, I could decide that the optimal tree size is 10. When the complexity reaches 10, the test MSE nearly obtains its lowest point among the attempts. In addition, ince simply increasing the complexity could cause over-fitting problem, I would not increase the tree size to numbers greater 10.
